Q23: I loved laughing and joking around with close friends as early as I can remember, but never gave thought to pursuing anything to do with it. I became lost after (for a variety of reasons both in & out of my control) hockey slipped away from me at age 16 and got into substance abuse. At 17, I had ‘an incident’ with Acid and was diagnosed as LSD psychotic. It was a horrible time. I saw countless psychiatrists, and was ill to the point of being offered an indefinite home as an in-patient at a Psychiatric unit for such disorders - many of the patients remained there for life. I was heavily medicated on anti-psychotics, and decided against that, instead opting to be an out-patient. Extensive therapy helped immensely, but two things truly changed my world for the better. 1) watching Seinfeld and laughing my ass off, and 2) writing what typically ended up being humorous twists on life as a whole. I pursued the writing in high school as a journalism student, and through a variety of fortunate events and insights into why I enjoyed writing, I began to suspect that Stand Up Comedy, something Id never watched or in any way shape or form aspired to do, may be ultimately what I’d enjoy doing, so I tried it, and I was right. Hook, line, and sinker, I was caught.

Q23:
I realize this survey has to ask broad questions with simple categories to make the data quantifiable or whatever, but jeeeeeesus christ what a paltry mix of hack questions this is. This is a Harvard survey? Do better ffs. 
Mental health isn't easily definable. Neither is being a 'comedian'. Especially in this day and age of every goon who experiences a desire to leave their cubicle job thinking slinging jokes is their best exit route. 
The stupidest focus of this survey is its attempt to locate a causal link between comedy and depression. This is a chicken and egg scenario. I had a shitty life, gallows humor saw me through it, when I found out what being a comedian was (I was 15) I decided I was going to be it and that was that. I'm sure being a comedian contributes to my depression/ bipolarness what with its highs and lows and its insanely brutal feedback system. But I was already living life like this before I set foot on stage, so who knows?

Q23: I don't specifically have any mental illness, and I'm happy to help in this survey, but one thing I've thought a lot about, when the questions have been asked about whether "sadness" or "depression" go hand in hand with comedy, is... what percentage of NON-comedians, NON-artists also contend with mental health issues. My understanding is that a large percentage of the population in general is medicated, and most people aren't comedians. It does seem that comedians are some of the most VOCAL people about their mental health issues, because that is sometimes the nature of the art and craft of comedy. You don't hear how many plumbers are depressed because it's not their job to speak about it, whereas it can be for a comedian. I'm also curious as to, even amongst comedians, are comedians with mental health issues more likely to even fill out this survey? I wish you the best in your study, and look forward to hearing about the results, should that be possible eventually.
